<PageLayout
  title="Busbar vs LiteLLM"
  description="An honest comparison for engineers deciding between Busbar and LiteLLM: protocol handling, failure behavior, runtime footprint, and when each is the right call."
>
  <p class="kicker">Comparison</p>
  <h1>Busbar vs LiteLLM</h1>
  <p class="intro">
    Everybody evaluating Busbar knows LiteLLM, so this page is specific about what's actually
    different. It isn't a feature list. LiteLLM is genuinely good at what it is: a Python-native
    router with huge provider coverage. Busbar is a different kind of tool, and the difference
    shows up in three places: how protocols are handled, what happens when a provider fails, and
    what the gateway itself costs you at runtime. Every claim about LiteLLM below is cited to
    their own documentation, and every claim about Busbar to ours.
  </p>

  <h2>The short version</h2>
  <div class="cmp">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th></th><th>Busbar</th><th>LiteLLM</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Core format</td>
          <td>No privileged protocol: one internal superset format every protocol maps into and out of, so all six are first-class in both directions</td>
          <td>OpenAI-shaped core; native-format ingress via per-protocol adapters <a href="#references">[4]</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Native ingress + load balancing</td>
          <td>All six protocols, simultaneously, on any pool</td>
          <td>Anthropic <code>/v1/messages</code> goes through the router <a href="#references">[4]</a>; byte-exact native routes are pass-throughs that skip it <a href="#references">[5]</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Bedrock SDK ingress</td>
          <td>A signed boto3 client, load-balanced across non-Bedrock backends, response re-encoded as valid binary eventstream</td>
          <td>Pass-through to Bedrock only <a href="#references">[5]</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Failure classification</td>
          <td>Fault-attributed: provider outage, auth/billing, client fault, and context-length each handled differently, per (pool, lane)</td>
